(:kind :chapter :book "Reference Manual" :chapter-number 6 :title "Chapter 6 — The metacircular evaluator" :source-path "git://origin/main/scheme-books/reference/06-metacircular.md" :size 2720 :sha256 "40f024cda6ec934f" :content "---\nslug: sakura-scheme-book-reference-06\ntitle: The metacircular evaluator\nbook: reference\nchapter: 6\nof: 16\npart: I\napp: scheme-repl\npalette: book-standard\ncanonical: true\nowner: docs-team (Lane Q9)\nstatus: draft\nlast-reviewed: 2026-07-10\nprev: 05-sicp-flavor\nnext: 07-streams\n---\n\n# Chapter 6 — The metacircular evaluator\n\nThe Scheme classic: a Scheme interpreter written in Scheme. This chapter walks a tiny one — enough to see the shape.\n\n> **Sakura says**\n>\n> When you can write Scheme's evaluator in Scheme, the language stops feeling like a tool and starts feeling like a fabric. The evaluator is the pattern; every program is a fold of that pattern.\n\n## The core\n\n```scheme\n(define (eval-form form env)\n  (cond\n    ((number? form) form)\n    ((symbol? form) (lookup form env))\n    ((eq? (car form) 'quote) (cadr form))\n    ((eq? (car form) 'if)\n     (if (eval-form (cadr form) env)\n         (eval-form (caddr form) env)\n         (eval-form (cadddr form) env)))\n    (else (apply-form (eval-form (car form) env)\n                       (map (lambda (a) (eval-form a env)) (cdr form))))))\n\n(display '(eval-form-shape-numbers-symbols-quote-if-application)) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n(eval-form-shape-numbers-symbols-quote-if-application)\n```\n\nFive cases cover most of it: literal number, variable lookup, quote, if, and application.\n\n## Environments\n\n```scheme\n(define (make-env bindings parent)\n  (list 'env bindings parent))\n\n(define (lookup name env)\n  (cond\n    ((null? env) (error 'unbound name))\n    ((assoc name (list-ref env 1)) => cadr)\n    (else (lookup name (list-ref env 2)))))\n\n(display 'env-is-a-frame-plus-parent) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\nenv-is-a-frame-plus-parent\n```\n\n## Apply\n\n```scheme\n(define (apply-form proc args)\n  (cond\n    ((procedure? proc) (proc . args))\n    ((eq? (car proc) 'lambda)\n     (eval-form (caddr proc) (make-env (map cons (cadr proc) args) 'env)))))\n\n(display 'apply-form-shape-primitive-or-lambda) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\napply-form-shape-primitive-or-lambda\n```\n\n## Define\n\n```scheme\n(display '(define-form-mutates-current-env-binding)) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n(define-form-mutates-current-env-binding)\n```\n\n## What you know now\n\n- The metacircular evaluator is Scheme in Scheme.\n- Five cases: number, symbol, quote, if, application.\n- Environments are frames-plus-parent lookup chains.\n- Apply dispatches primitives vs lambdas.\n\n## Try before you turn the page\n\n```scheme\n(display '(scheme-in-scheme-is-a-mirror)) (newline)\n```\n\nIf you can name the five eval cases, you're ready for streams.\n\n---\n\nCross-references:\n\n- [[book-of-reference#chapter-4]] — macros.\n- [[book-of-reference#chapter-7]] — streams.\n- [[book-of-one-shot#chapter-1]] — one-form.\n")
